You&#39;re right that Firebase Storage operations are asynchronous, and the code you provided may not guarantee that the **articles** list is populated when you expect it to be. To ensure that your **articles** list is populated only after all the data has been retrieved from Firebase Storage, you can use `Tasks.whenAll()` to handle the asynchronous calls. Here&#39;s how you can modify your code to achieve that:

    public class NewActivity extends AppCompatActivity {
        
        List&lt;Article&gt; articles = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    
        protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
            super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
            setContentView(R.layout.activity_themes);
    
            FirebaseApp.initializeApp(NewActivity.this);
            FirebaseDatabase database = FirebaseDatabase.getInstance();
            FirebaseStorage storage = FirebaseStorage.getInstance();
    
            StorageReference reference = storage.getReference(&quot;themes&quot;);
            reference.listAll().addOnSuccessListener(new OnSuccessListener&lt;ListResult&gt;() {
                @Override
                public void onSuccess(ListResult listResult) {
                    List&lt;Task&lt;Void&gt;&gt; tasks = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    
                    for (StorageReference prefix : listResult.getPrefixes()) {
                        Task&lt;Void&gt; task = getArticleNameAndAddToList(prefix);
                        tasks.add(task);
                    }
    
                    Tasks.whenAll(tasks).addOnSuccessListener(new OnSuccessListener&lt;Void&gt;() {
                        @Override
                        public void onSuccess(Void aVoid) {
                            // Now, the articles list is populated.
                        }
                    }).addOnFailureListener(new OnFailureListener() {
                        @Override
                        public void onFailure(@NonNull Exception e) {
                            e.printStackTrace();
                        }
                    });
                }
            });
        }
    
        private Task&lt;Void&gt; getArticleNameAndAddToList(StorageReference reference) {
            TaskCompletionSource&lt;Void&gt; taskCompletionSource = new TaskCompletionSource&lt;&gt;();
            
            reference.getName().addOnSuccessListener(new OnSuccessListener&lt;String&gt;() {
                @Override
                public void onSuccess(String name) {
                    articles.add(new Article(name));
                    taskCompletionSource.setResult(null);
                }
            }).addOnFailureListener(new OnFailureListener() {
                @Override
                public void onFailure(@NonNull Exception e) {
                    taskCompletionSource.setException(e);
                }
            });
            
            return taskCompletionSource.getTask();
        }
    }

In this code:

&gt; **1.** We create a list of tasks for retrieving folder names using nameTask.
&gt; 
&gt; **2.** We use onSuccessTask to create a new task for each folder name
&gt; retrieval. This allows you to add the folder name to the articles list
&gt; and continue the chain of tasks.
&gt; 
&gt; **3.** We use Tasks.whenAll(tasks) to wait for all the tasks to complete,
&gt; ensuring that the articles list is fully populated before proceeding
&gt; with any further actions.
&gt; 
&gt; **4.** Now, the articles list will be populated with folder names only after
&gt; all the data has been successfully retrieved from Firebase Storage.

