answers.body_markdown:
[![Various situation encountered while doing the search][1]][1]



As shown, above there could be various situations encountered while doing the search, the minimum element could be in the right half of the array, as shown in the Picture 1. If we compare the mid value with the 0th index value, then mid is greater and hence we have to move to the right to get the minimum value under the assumption that rotation is there. But it could be that the array is sorted but not at all rotated or it is rotated the same as the number of elements in the array. In that case our choice of moving to the right by setting lo = mid + 1 is plain wrong. Hence choosing the firstVal, which is at index 0, as comparison point, in this particular application of Binary Search is wrong.

Let&#39;s check the case of selecting the last value of the array as the comparison point. 

If the minimum is in the right half, then mid is greater than the end value, so we move lo to the mid + 1.

If the mid is less than the end value, i.e value at the last index, then we move hi to mid, as that very value at mid could be the minimum value, so we are not going mid - 1.

Now let&#39;s see if the array is not at all rotated or similar situations, then the minimum is at the 0th index, so if we go the mid index value, we get a value which is less than the end value (value at the last index), so it makes sense that we move to the left of the mid. Remember we had taken the same decision of moving to the left when the minimum was in the first half and there also the mid was less than the end value.
So moving to the left is correct in all aspects of rotated or unrotated array.
Hence we should solve the above problem with the end value, for an easy straightforward solution.

But it&#39;s nobody&#39;s case that this problem can not be solved with comparing the mid index with the value at the 0th index value.
It can be done, only thing the solution will have to handle the ambiguity resulting from the below shown two kind of cases :-

[![The ambiguous situations encountered while considering the first index value][2]][2]





This can be solved by adding an extra condition, if the mid value ia greater than the value at lo, then there are two situations either the array is rotated and the minimum is on the right half, as shown in the first picture above.
Or
the array is not rotated or is rotated so much that all the elements have come back to their original positions.

We can tackle these two situations by adding an extra condition in the code :-

    class Solution {
        public int findMin(int[] nums){
            int lo = 0, hi = nums.length - 1, mid = -1, firstVal = nums[lo];
            while(lo &lt; hi){
                mid = (lo + hi) &gt;&gt;&gt; 1;
                if(nums[mid] &gt;= firstVal){// if mid val is greater or equal to the first val, then the min is either on the left if the array is unrotated, or in the right half. If unrotated then the first value will be always less than or equal to the end value. Otherwise the first value will be always greater than the end value
                    if(nums[lo] &lt;= nums[hi]){ // this one checks if the array is sorted
                        hi = mid;
                    }else { // if not sorted and the first index value is less than the one at mid, the the minimum must be after the mid in the right half
                        lo = mid + 1;
                    }
                }else{
                    hi = mid;
                }
