The key issue with comparing with the first value (often referred to as &quot;lo&quot;) is ambiguity in situations where the array might be rotated back to its original sorted order (or not rotated at all). In this case, it&#39;s hard to determine which direction to move in based on that comparison alone.  When comparing the &quot;mid&quot; value with the &quot;hi&quot; value, we have a clear direction:-


 

 1. If &quot;mid&quot; is greater than &quot;hi&quot;, the minimum value (or rotation start)
        is to the right of &quot;mid&quot;. 
    
 2. If &quot;mid&quot; is less than or equal to &quot;hi&quot;,
        the minimum value (or rotation start) is at &quot;mid&quot; or to the left of
        it.

So in this sense, the &quot;hi&quot; comparison more straightforward and effective for this specific problem.

 


